In your case the easiest would probably be to use st-safe-src attribute and re assign the watched collection so you are sure the sort is kicked on new values.

```Javascript
$scope.updateRow = (row, newRow) => {
  const index = $scope.rowCollection.indexOf(row);
  if(index !== -1) {
    const newDataSet = [...$scope.rowCollection];
    newDataSet.splice(index, 1, newRow);
    $scope.rowCollection = newDataSet; // assign new reference, the watch should be kicked
  }
}
```

I don't think setting as attribute the way things should be watched is a good thing to do, It is more related to angular internals and it seems to be already complicated to grasp with stSafeSrc attribute

