Hi - not sure whether this is the same problem, but BaseAdapter.expand() fails in Python 2.7 with a UnicodeEncodeError in line 935 if the expression is a unicode containing non-ASCII characters.

There is some urgency to this as it has gone into web2py 2.11.1-stable (sorry for pushing, but we really need this fixed in web2py, not just in pyDAL trunk - unfortunately the project separation has lead to serious delays before pyDAL fixes become available in web2py).

The particular case is:
"Icelandic Red Cross (Rauða krossinn)" is the expression, being an UTF-8 encoded str.

BaseAdapter.represent decodes it here:

        if PY2:
            if not isinstance(obj, bytes):
                obj = bytes(obj)
            try:
                obj.decode(self.db_codec) # <= here, db_codec being UTF-8
            except:
                obj = obj.decode('latin1').encode(self.db_codec)
        else:
            obj = to_unicode(obj)

...which converts it into a unicode.

But then, BaseAdapter.expand() does just try to str(rv) this unicode:

        else:
            rv = expression
        return str(rv) # <= here, not taking care of non-ASCII characters in unicodes

which will necessarily fail for any non-ASCII character in the unicode - but non-ASCII characters are the whole point of it being a unicode in the first place (!), so this seems wrong.

I added this as a workaround:

        if isinstance(rv, unicode):
            # Make sure non-ASCII code points are dealt with:
            return rv.encode(self.db_codec) # <= this produces an UTF-8 encoded str
        else:
            return str(rv)

which makes it work for me (having the db_codec being UTF-8). Surely this could still fail if db_codec is ASCII or Latin1 - but then that's correct as the DB wouldn't support it either.

Could you fix this, maybe quickly (since it affects web2py stable)? Many thanks.

