This is not a bug.  The design was exactly as @matsjoyce states.  If you look at the source for `cloudpickle`, you'll see that a disproportionate amount of it is to determine which objects are dependencies of an object's `__globals__`.  I didn't want to just port that code into `dill`, because it's quite long, and more importantly, not a robust solution.  The `dill` solution, for now, is to avoid the issue -- and it works surprisingly well in most cases.

That being said, the `pyspark` guys have a very similar request ( https://github.com/uqfoundation/dill/pull/86), which I have reworked into two function calls… one to get all globals required to serialize an object, and the other to only find the globals that are referenced in the local scope.  My version of the patch has not been applied, but is pretty much ready to get committed.  I have not had time of late to get back and tie up the issue/PR.

@mrocklin: take a look at #86 and see if it's basically what you are looking for.  This is only major feature that I'd say that `cloudpickle` has that `dill` doesn't.  However, when the patch is applied, `dill` should have a version that is less fragile than what is in `cloudpickle`.

